This program builds a CNN (Convolutional Neural Network) using TensorFlow/Keras to recognize handwritten digits from the MNIST dataset (0–9).

Step-by-Step Short Explanation
1. Import Libraries
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import datasets, layers, models
tensorflow → Deep Learning library
datasets → loads MNIST dataset
layers → used to create CNN layers
models → used to build the neural network model
2. Load Dataset
(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test) = datasets.mnist.load_data()
Loads MNIST handwritten digit images.
X_train → training images
y_train → training labels
X_test → testing images
y_test → testing labels

Each image size = 28 × 28 pixels

3. Normalize Data
X_train = X_train / 255.0
X_test = X_test / 255.0

Pixel values are between 0–255.

Dividing by 255 converts them to 0–1 range.

This helps the model train faster and better.

4. Reshape Images
X_train = X_train.reshape(-1, 28, 28, 1)
X_test = X_test.reshape(-1, 28, 28, 1)

CNN expects 4D input:

(samples, height, width, channels)
28 → image height
28 → image width
1 → grayscale channel
5. Build CNN Model
model = models.Sequential([

Sequential() means layers are added one after another.

First Convolution Layer
layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(28,28,1))
Applies 32 filters of size 3×3
Detects image features like edges/shapes
ReLU activation removes negative values
First Pooling Layer
layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2))
Reduces image size
Keeps important features
Makes training faster
Second Convolution Layer
layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu')
Uses 64 filters
Learns more complex features
Second Pooling Layer
layers.MaxPooling2D((2,2))

Again reduces feature map size.

Flatten Layer
layers.Flatten()

Converts 2D feature maps into 1D vector for Dense layers.

Dense Hidden Layer
layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')

Fully connected layer with 64 neurons.

Output Layer
layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')
10 neurons → digits 0 to 9
softmax gives probability of each digit
6. Compile Model
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
Optimizer

adam → updates weights efficiently.

Loss Function

sparse_categorical_crossentropy → used for multi-class classification.

Metric

accuracy → checks prediction accuracy.

7. Train Model
model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=3)
Trains CNN using training data
epochs=3 means dataset is trained 3 times
8. Evaluate Model
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)

Checks model performance on unseen test data.

9. Print Accuracy
print("Test Accuracy:", test_acc)

Displays final test accuracy.

Usually accuracy is around 98%.

